Public procurement of works and prevention of corruption
Joint report by the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NK) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel audits
Introduction and overview
The award of services by public authorities is of great importance for the state as well as for the economy.
The state has the task of using public funds as economically and economically as possible, as well as ensuring fair and regulated competition.
In the European Union (EU), the award of services by public authorities is an important element in the creation of a single economic area.
In order to be able to ensure a largely unrestricted competition across borders, the contracting authorities have to comply with EU requirements for their contracts above certain value limits (thresholds).
For this purpose, the EU member states have to transfer and apply the EU's public procurement law into national law.
This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.
It is up to individual countries to regulate the award of public contracts below the EU threshold.
In addition, the award of services is also an area at risk of corruption.
Due to the fundamentally high potential for damages, the contracting authorities therefore have to implement appropriate measures to prevent corruption and inadmissible benefits in the award of their contracts and to prevent them.
In January 2011, the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (NCA) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed to carry out parallel audits for the EU-wide allocation of construction services as well as for the prevention of corruption.
The tests focused on the application of the EU public procurement law, which has been transposed into national regulations, as well as the prevention of corruption in the award of construction services in the construction, road construction and transport infrastructure.
The awards below the EU threshold were also included in the considerations with regard to the prevention of corruption.
The audit results of both courts are summarised in this joint report.
The report should also be addressed to international bodies, such as the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).
Auditing areas and audited bodies The evaluations of the Federal Audit Office on the listed topics are mainly based on cross-sectional audits, which he carried out in 2011 / 2012 in the construction services, which are responsible for the construction of roads and buildings of the Federal Government in Germany.
He examined, for example, the construction of motorways and major construction projects.
In addition, the Federal Audit Office drew on results from previous investigations.
From 2008 to 2011, the Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic based its evaluations of the results of the examinations, which included construction measures in road construction, railway track construction, hydroelectric construction, building construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.) and other construction areas in the Czech Republic.
The award of public contracts by the federal government is mainly carried out in Germany by the building services of the federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the state building administration is centrally responsible for public contracts in the field of transport infrastructure.
In the construction, the contracts are carried out in a decentralized manner by those bodies that use the state budget.
In both countries, freelancers will also be involved in parts of the tendering procedures.
When comparing the evaluations, differences in the procurement law and the market structure for construction services in both countries must be taken into account.
Development of public procurement law in both countries
In Germany, the implementation of EU-wide tendering procedures is laid down in laws and regulations.
Procurement procedures limited to the national area are governed by budgetary law and the administrative provisions that are based on it.
In addition, for both EU-wide and national awards, many complementary individual regulations are provided for by internal administrative provisions,
Such as the so-called "award books" of the Federal Government, in which the legal requirements are supplemented or formulated in greater detail, in accordance with the law on public procurement.
In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure is governed exclusively by the Public Procurement Act and other legal requirements, which apply to areas above and below EU thresholds.
The law on public procurement was significantly amended in 2012.
The new regulation increased transparency in the handling of public funds, allowed for greater competition and limited the opportunities for corruption in the procurement procedure.
Guidelines of public procurement law in both countries
In both countries, EU-wide contracts are subject in particular to the open procedure, the non-open procedure and the negotiation procedure.
In Germany, the measures below the EU threshold are subject to the national types of tendering (public tender, limited tender, open-ended award), which, however, largely correspond to the EU-wide types of tendering mentioned above.
Public procurement law in Germany is characterised by the principle of priority of the open procedure (for EU-wide contracts) and the public tender procedure (for national contracts).
Any interested company can submit an offer at the open procedure and at the public tender.
Another essential feature of German public procurement law is the promotion of medium-sized enterprises.
The division of an overall construction project into technical and partial ones serves this purpose above all.
The individual award of these lots is intended to enable as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.
Both of the above features of German public procurement law are proven tools for achieving economic results.
In Germany there are over 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees.
In the Czech Republic, EU-wide tendering procedures are also applicable to projects below the EU threshold.
An exception here is the simplified procedure, in which a less stringent procedure may be applied below the thresholds and under certain conditions.
Czech public procurement law, in accordance with EU law, provides for contracts to be concluded if competition is guaranteed and a favourable price is achieved.
The current legal regulations in the Czech Republic allow contracting authorities to choose between the open and the not open procedure.
There are over 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, including around 1,900 companies with 20 or more employees.
Volume of public contracts and shares of the types of contracts in both countries
In Germany, the total construction volume in 2011 was 307 billion euros.
Of this, public construction (15%) accounted for 45.5 billion euros, which includes, in addition to the federal construction, in particular the construction measures of the federal states and municipalities.
The construction volume of the federal government in the construction and construction of highways (without railway track construction and hydroelectric construction) amounted to 8.5 billion euros.
The volume of contracts for construction services in the construction and highway construction of the federal government was distributed among the types of contracts in 2011 as follows: 80.7% open procedures and public tenders, 12.7% not open procedures and restricted tenders and 6.6% negotiation procedures and public contracts.
Of these, 33.2% were Europe-wide contracts.
The volume of public works in the Czech Republic amounted to 4.7 billion Euros in 2011, which was about 25% of the total volume of all construction projects in the Czech Republic.
In 2009, the volume was 7.8 billion euros, corresponding to 37% of the total construction volume.
Breakdown by type of tender for 2011: 65.1% open procedure, 14.3% non-public procedure, 9.5% negotiation procedure, 8.4% simplified procedure for volume of contracts, below the 2.7% threshold
The data refer to all public contracts for deliveries, services and construction services awarded by public contracting authorities in 2011.
The above data show that the parallel audits of both countries are directed at a significant part of public contracts, which are of great financial importance in the prevention of corruption in all contracts, and which have a prominent place in the award of contracts through the open procedure and the public tender.
Summary of the results of the parallel tests
The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic (NK) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) have carried out parallel audits in their countries for the EU-wide allocation of construction services and for the prevention of corruption.
In this context, the working groups of both courts compared the appropriate legal bases and administrative requirements in the Czech Republic and Germany, as well as the results of their parallel audits, which they carried out in particular in the fields of construction and road construction.
In doing so, they found essentially:
The EU directives on the award of works by public authorities have been transposed into national law in both the Czech Republic and Germany (points 1 and 3.1).
In addition to the EU requirements, the two countries' public procurement regulations, which differ in part in their focus and detail, serve to prevent corruption (No. 3.2).
In both countries, a fundamental requirement of the award documents is that they must contain all the information required for the proper preparation of an offer.
The performance descriptions must be neutral and must not be subject to advertising restrictions.
In Germany, the award documents have largely complied with these requirements.
In the Czech Republic, it is still a problem to determine the object of the order sufficiently.
In Germany, construction services have to be divided into lots, if possible, in order to promote competition.
According to the findings of the BRH, this requirement has been largely implemented in Germany.
In its tests, especially in the field of road construction, the NCA found that the award of extensive services without lots or with very large lots can hamper competition and lead to a restriction on only a few large companies.
Narrowing the market potential can lead to significant increases in costs and risk price or other collusion.
According to the regulations of both countries, the contracting bodies can, under certain conditions, in principle agree with the already commissioned companies on additional or amended services, which prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (No. 4.1).
The respective requirements for determining the type of contract were largely followed in both countries.
According to the regulations of the Czech Republic, the awarding bodies can choose between open and non-open procedures.
In Germany, on the other hand, the priority of the open procedure for EU-wide tenders, which corresponds to the open procedure for national contracts, is legally and budgetary.
This will allow more companies to make offers.
This reduces the risk of corruption, makes price fixing between bidders more difficult and leads to the most economic results.
In the case of construction projects whose estimated total contract values reached or exceeded the EU threshold, the audited building services awarded the construction services in principle throughout Europe.
The correct estimation of the expected contract value is an essential basis for choosing the right type of contract.
In Germany, cost databases are used to determine the costs of public buildings, in particular in the construction sector.
Which are based on the evaluations of completed construction projects.
In the Czech Republic, a database is used in the field of road construction, but it is not yet an effective instrument (No. 4.2).
Preliminary information and announcements are to be published for construction services to be awarded throughout Europe, which should strengthen the competition by enabling interested companies to adapt to the planned contracts at an early stage.
The audited building services generally complied with this requirement.
In individual cases, incorrect information, incorrect applications or a lack of controls may affect competition (point 4.3).
The selection of candidates for participation in non-public procurement procedures is particularly susceptible to manipulation.
Under EU law, the number of invited candidates must be sufficiently high to ensure genuine competition.
The selection criteria must be objective, must not discriminate and must be disclosed beforehand.
In addition to the requirements of the EU, the contracting bodies in both countries should switch among the companies to be required as frequently as possible when selecting the candidates.
In order to counter the threat of manipulation, there are in some cases very detailed guidelines in Germany.
In some cases, the audited administrations disregarded these requirements.
In the Czech Republic, decisions on the selection of candidates were not always comprehensible (point 4.4).
In both countries, during the bidding phase, in the interests of equal competition, it must be ensured that the companies interested in submitting an offer receive the same information.
To avoid anti-competitive collusion, a contact between these companies and freelancers, who were involved in the creation of the service description, must be avoided as far as possible.
The corresponding regulations in Germany are more extensive than in the Czech Republic.
However, the audited building services in Germany sometimes did not comply with these requirements (No. 4.5).
When opening the offers, the principle of transparency and the principle of multi-eyes must be observed in both countries.
The requirements for marking, documentation, custody and confidentiality of the offers are intended to limit the scope for manipulation and are particularly well defined in Germany.
Tests in both countries showed few complaints (point 4.6).
In both countries, the assessment and evaluation of the offers are determined by requirements for the organisation of construction and the organisation of operations.
The regulations in Germany are more comprehensive, but have not been consistently observed by the audited contracting bodies.
For example, awarding agencies passed on offers for inspection to third parties, without first looking through the offers and sufficiently documenting conspicuous events.
As a result, the offers were insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulation (No. 4.7).
At the conclusion of the EU-wide tendering procedures, the companies taking part in the competition will be informed of the intended assignment prior to the award of the contract.
This legal protection also has a preventive function against corrupt behaviour.
The Czech Republic also provides for the possibility of judicial review for non-EU tendering procedures.
Only in a few cases did the awarding authorities not respect the specified deadlines in the award of contracts or deviate from the bidders' offer in terms of content (point 4.8).
The documentation of the tendering procedures was not always complete or comprehensible for the audited building services in both countries.
In this respect, the EU-wide requirement for transparency was not sufficiently implemented in the award notices of some procedures.
Also, some of the shortcomings identified diminished the anti-corruption function of the documentation.
The contracting authorities of both countries largely complied with their reporting and reporting obligations (point 4.9).
Foundations of EU public procurement law and the prevention of corruption
EU public procurement law
In order to ensure unrestricted competition within the European Union with free movement of services and goods, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, among other things, the award coordination and appeal directives, which were to be transposed into national law by the eight Member States.
The general award principles of the European Union are, in particular, the principle of competition, the principle of equal treatment or the prohibition of discrimination, as well as the requirement of transparency.
In order to achieve these objectives, the award coordination directive contains specific regulations for building services to be awarded across the EU for construction projects.
In order to do this, their prospective orders must reach or exceed the current sum of 5,000,000 euros.
The regulations concern in particular the content of the award documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, the adherence to deadlines, inter alia for the receipt of the bids, the documentation of the award procedure, the requirements that can be placed on the qualification of the candidates and the appeal directive forms the basis for the legal protection of the applicants and bidders.
In the case of possible violations of public procurement law, affected companies can have the decisions of public contracting authorities reviewed in review proceedings.
Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the directives of the European Union into national law.
Prevention of corruption
The importance of preventing corruption
There is no legal definition of corruption in either country.
Generally, corruption is the abuse of a position of trust for private gain,
Which is usually caused by the beneficiaries of these decisions.
Corruption can hamper competition and cause significant economic damage.
It is estimated that the global cost of corruption is 5% of the world's economic output.
For the European Union, the cost is estimated at 1%.
In the case of public contracting companies, restrictive agreements or unfair practices can call into question confidence in the integrity and functioning of the administration.
Preventing corruption is therefore one of the basic tasks of public authorities.
In doing so, they will have to check the structure and organisation of their administrations for areas that are particularly susceptible to corruption, in order to make appropriate safeguards against corruption.
Preventive measures and effective controls can significantly reduce the vulnerability of decision-making processes to corrupt abuse.
The award of public works is generally regarded as a particularly corrupt area of work.
Anti-corruption measures
In Germany, corruption - in particular bribery and bribery, as well as the acceptance and approval of benefits - is prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
In order to prevent corruption, the Federal Government has adopted a guideline and recommendations on the prevention of corruption 12 in the federal administration, according to which, in addition to risk analysis, the following basic principles must be observed for the award area: Priority of public tenders and open procedures, the principle of transparency and transparency, the basic separation of planning, awarding and settlement, the proper and complete documentation of procurement procedures.
In addition, further anti-corruption requirements have been incorporated into the public procurement rules.
In 2011, for example, the responsible Federal Ministry of Public Procurement introduced an electronic control system in the area of the federal highways,
The award data - such as the estimated costs and the amount of the order - as well as information on the freelancers involved are collected across the board and evaluated for abnormalities.
In the Czech Republic, corruption is also prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
The legal requirements of transparency and equal treatment of bidders, as well as the prohibition of all discrimination, are the most important principles for preventing corruption.
For public procurement, the Czech government has defined anti-corruption measures in a anti-corruption strategy paper for the years 2011 to 2012 and updated them for the years 2013 to 2014.
Some of the measures recommended in it have already been transposed into national public procurement law and corresponding administrative provisions 14.
The new legislation contains essentially the following rules: Reduction of the threshold for smaller contracts, obligation to make the tenders known to the tendering authority in advance, including the reasons for the tender, prohibition of the restriction of the number of bidders in non-open procedures and thus the abolition of the possibility of bidding by means of lots, introduction of the obligation to publish the contract documents and all the annexes, introduction of the obligation to publish the actual price and the list of subcontractors.
Examination results of the various phases of the award procedure
Tender documents
Award Documents The award documents must contain all the information that bidders need to make a proper bid.
In particular, the award documents must enable a valid calculation.
The bidders must not be given risks that are not calculable for them.
The award documents consist in particular of the description of services and the terms of the contract.
In addition, they contain the requirements for proving the qualifications (suitability) of the bidders as well as the criteria that determine the selection of the most economical bids.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption
The requirements of EU law for the award documents are specifically addressed to the technical specifications.
These must be equally accessible to all bidders and should restrict competition as little as possible.
The performance description must be product neutral in principle.
For this reason, information on products or manufacturers as part of the service description is only permitted under strict conditions.
Avoiding anti-competitive requirements in the procurement documents is also a fundamental principle of preventing corruption.
In addition, unclear or incorrect information in the award documents must be avoided, as they open up scope for speculation in the production of the offers and for manipulations in their valuation.
Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law
Similar or similar regulations In both countries, EU regulations on technical specifications have been transposed into national law.
In principle, the services are product-neutral without tendering factory specifications.
In the service descriptions, the individual services must normally be subdivided into performance units with specific quantity specifications.
Prices are to be agreed on the basis of performance units (e.g. Euro per m ² or per piece).
Only in exceptional cases can services be defined by functional targets.
In any case, the descriptions must be complete and unambiguous.
They must contain precise figures and must not include services where it is not clear whether they are needed.
Compensation by lump sum or time is to be avoided if possible.
These provisions are intended to prevent speculation and manipulation based on unspecified requirements in the award documents.
The service descriptions must enable bidders to make their offers safely and without extensive preparatory work.
The tender will not be made public until the tender documents have been completed.
Divergent regulations
There is no obligation to tender for construction services in lots in the Czech Republic.
If it is possible according to the type of service to be supervised, the public contracting authorities can divide construction services into several lots.
In Germany, construction services are to be divided into lots, separated by quantity (partial) and / or by type or specialism (non-skilled).
The aim is to enable medium-sized companies to participate in the competition, to expand the number of possible suppliers and to make it more difficult to agree on prices.
This type of award is considered to be the most economical in general.
Evaluation criteria in the Czech Republic must be specified in the award documents, both in the EU-wide and in the national procedures.
This will allow applicants to be fully and conclusively aware of the criteria under which their offers are to be evaluated.
In Germany, the specification of evaluation criteria in EU-wide notices, but at the latest in the award documents, is only required in EU-wide tendering procedures.
In the case of national tendering procedures, the evaluation criteria should only be recorded in an internal administrative notice.
Procurement documents, which are prepared by commissioned freelancers, must not contain any information on these offices or on the planners or experts involved in building construction or road construction in Germany.
The aim is to prevent individual companies from gaining additional information or other illegal competitive advantages without the knowledge of the client about the contact with these freelancers.
This is also the reason why freelancers are not allowed to send tendering documents or interpret planning documents for inspection.
The company's contact person is the client alone.
There is currently no regulation in the Czech Republic.
Additional or amended services, which prove to be necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (amendments), are almost always required for large construction projects.
In both countries, the legal provisions make it possible, to a certain extent, to award additional sums to the company that has already been commissioned, without the need for a public procurement procedure.
According to the EU guidelines and the German regulations, the compensation of supplementary benefits may not exceed half of the main mandate.
In addition, the additional services cannot be separated from the main contract without significant disadvantages or must be absolutely necessary.
In the Czech Republic, a tighter limit of 20% applies to a corresponding award without public notice.
However, this may increase the risk of delayed completion of the project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the construction work that is already underway.
If supplementary payments are also transferred to the already commissioned company, an arbitrary price increase for these services by the contractor is in principle not possible according to the regulations in Germany.
In determining the compensation for the additional services, it is to be assumed that the agreed prices and the basis of the price calculation of the order already issued are the basis.
In addition to supplementary benefits, there may also be a reduction in the scope of services.
In the Czech Republic, it is not possible to charge smaller amounts with additional supplementary payments.
