Further findings
Based on a sampling of construction projects, the NK found that the average cost of building a four-lane motorway in the Czech Republic is up to 14.6 million euros.
In Deuschland, on the other hand, according to an analysis of long-term data from the Federal Ministry of Building, the average cost of a four-lane motorway is up to 10.4 million euros.
This comparison suggests that highway construction in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in Germany.
Summary findings
The basic regulations on the award documents are broadly in agreement in both countries and take into account the EU requirements.
They serve both comprehensive and fair competition and the prevention of corruption.
For example, the requirement for the sufficient determination of the service descriptions should enable bidders to properly calculate and create their offers,
Protect the client from additional services to be subsequently agreed and also limit the scope for speculation.
In Germany, the common basic requirements for the award documents are supplemented by regulations that further reduce competition restrictions and opportunities for manipulation.
In the Czech Republic there are no requirements to this extent, but transparency is increased by the publication of the evaluation criteria in non-EU tendering procedures.
The requirements for the performance description have been largely complied with in both countries.
In some cases, however, there have been objections, which may have led to restrictions on competition.
The imperative for the formation of lots in Germany promotes competition and leads to economic results.
In the Czech Republic, according to the audit findings of the NCO, the award of extensive services without lots or with very large lots can lead to restrictions of the provider field on only a few large companies.
The extensive reference requirements in road construction in the Czech Republic have meant that public contracts are only awarded to a narrow range of operators and small and medium-sized enterprises are not allowed to take part in the competition.
Also, a limited number of competitors often lead to higher prices and increase the risk of price or other collusion.
In the case of the award and remuneration of additional or modified services, the regulatory approaches in both countries differ.
According to the EU guidelines and the German regulations, supplementary services with a value of up to half of the main contract can be awarded under certain conditions without a public notice procedure.
In the Czech Republic, there is a tighter limit of 20%, up to which additional services can be awarded to the original contractor in the negotiation procedure without notice.
