Since the scope of services for public contracts is often insufficiently determined.
If the excess exceeds 20%, the additional services must be advertised with public notice.
By dividing services into lots, restrictions on competition and the resulting adverse effects can be avoided.
Setting the type of contract and taking into account the EU threshold
By specifying the type of contract, the client determines the number of companies participating in the competition.
It can leave the circle of potential candidates and bidders largely unrestricted, for example, by choosing an open procedure or by imposing non-public tendering procedures.
For construction projects that meet or exceed a threshold set by the EU, Europe-wide tendering procedures must be applied.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption
When choosing the type of contract, the contracting authority has to take into account, in particular, European bids for competition and transparency.
If the estimated total contract value of the construction services of a project is at or above the EU threshold of currently 5,000,000 Euros, construction services are to be awarded in principle throughout Europe according to open or non-open procedures.
In exceptional cases, negotiation procedures or competitive dialogue are also possible.
The contracting authority may, to a limited extent, deviate from the principle of Europe-wide contracting in construction projects that reach or exceed the EU threshold and award construction services in national contracts, provided that the estimated contract value of the respective lot is less than 1,000,000 euros and the sum of these lots does not exceed 20% of the estimated total contract value of all construction contracts.
A single construction project must not be divided into individual measures without any compelling reason or consciously valued at too low cost values, in order to deprive it of the obligation to award construction services across Europe in principle.
Since restrictions on competition significantly increase the risk of manipulation, the choice of the method of award is of great importance in the prevention of corruption.
The detailed reasoning of the chosen award method as well as the examination of the obligation to apply the EU procurement regulations are important components of the documentation of the award procedure.
Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
Both countries have fully transposed the EU legal requirements on tendering procedures and the threshold into national law.
Divergent regulations
The Czech Republic has also transferred the fundamental equivalence of open and non-open procedures contained in the EU directive to its construction contracts, which are not subject to EU requirements.
There is freedom of choice between the open and the not open procedure, without the decision being documented or substantiated, whereas other procedures are only possible according to certain legally defined conditions.
In Germany, on the other hand, the open procedure, or - in the case of national contracts - the public tender procedure, which is determined by budgetary and public procurement law as well as by the guidelines for the prevention of corruption, has priority.
Other types of tenders - such as the non-open procedure or the limited tender - are only possible in exceptional cases, which are finally regulated in public procurement law.
The existence of an exceptional case must be substantiated and documented.
The principle of the primacy of the open procedure or public tender is intended to ensure that competition is as unrestricted as possible, to exclude the possibility of manipulation by setting certain bidders and to make it more difficult for bidders to agree on prices.
The principle of public tendering is a central element in preventing corruption in Germany.
The correct estimation of the expected contract value is an essential basis for choosing the right type of contract.
The construction authorities in Germany can rely on planning and cost databases of public administrations and other organisations to determine the expected costs in the area of public construction.
These databases are based on evaluations of completed construction projects. Among other things, the databases contain cost specifications for building categories, use units, building elements or individual construction services.
On the basis of such cost parameters, the expected order value of a planned plan or a construction output to be awarded can be determined.
In Germany, only a few building services have corresponding cost databases for road construction.
However, a nationwide introduction for all road construction administrations is planned.
Contracting agencies in the Czech Republic cannot rely on central databases or average price estimates of comparable construction measures to determine the likely cost of construction services.
In most cases, the cost assessment is based on estimates by the financing authority or results from the amount of funds made available to the building services.
Measures to standardise cost assessment procedures are still in their infancy.
