Opening of offers
During the opening date, the previously closed offers will be opened and their contents read and thus made known.
From the opening date, bidders will be bound to their bids until the expiration of the award period set by the awarding authority.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption
There are no specific EU regulations for the opening up of bids.
However, the national regulations for the prevention of corruption contain extensive requirements for the protection of bids and competition for this highly sensitive phase of the tendering procedure.
The multi-eye principle and the transparency and traceability of the offer opening are intended to prevent manipulation and alteration of the submitted offers.
Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
The opening date must be carried out by several persons to be determined by the awarding authority.
The multi-eye principle is intended to prevent individuals from being able to manipulate the offers in an uncontrolled manner when opening the offers.
In most tendering procedures, bidders can attend the opening date.
Only offers are accepted for the opening, which were submitted to the head of the negotiations when the first bid was opened.
In principle, offers received late may no longer be considered.
In order to ensure the transparency of the opening date, the actions taken and the results of the opening of the bid must be set out in a protocol in which, among other things, the names of the bidders and the bid prices must be recorded.
The minutes are to be read and signed by the negotiators.
It can also be signed by the bidders present.
