Review and evaluation of the offers
Review and evaluation of the offers The client has to examine and evaluate the offers that are available at the opening date.
He has to determine the offer for the award of the award, which corresponds best to the requirements according to the given award criteria.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption
The EU guidelines provide for a multi-level procedure:
First of all, the suitability of the bidders must be established.
Bidders must be economically and financially efficient and have the necessary professional and technical expertise.
In principle, companies that have been convicted of, for example, bribery or fraud are to be excluded from participating in the award procedure.
The bids of the not excluded bidders are to be examined in terms of calculation, technology and economics and evaluated on the basis of the award criteria previously announced.
The client has to determine the most economical offer. Offers with unusually low prices have to be examined by the client in particular.
The review and evaluation of the bids is a particularly tamper-prone phase of the award procedure.
For example, bidders can be unjustly excluded or offers that do not meet the requirements can be left in the competition.
By favouring or discriminating against bidders, the result can be unacceptably impaired and thus the establishment of the most economically advantageous offer can be prevented.
The awarding authority must therefore take special precautions to ensure that the persons charged with the examination and evaluation meet the requirements for integrity and expertise.
It must also ensure the transparency and traceability of the procedure and the decisions taken.
Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
In accordance with the requirements of the EU, offers in both countries must be examined and evaluated in a multi-stage procedure.
The requirements for the proof of suitability of the companies to be submitted as well as the award criteria to be taken into account in the evaluation and their weighting are specified in the notices or in the award documents and can no longer be changed during the procedure.
After testing the suitability of the bidding, the suitability criteria may no longer be used in the evaluation of the bids.
The rating has to be limited to the award criteria.
The submitted bids must first be formally examined immediately to see if they are complete and if they contain, for example, abnormalities that could indicate possible manipulation intentions.
If bidders are excluded from further consideration and evaluation of their bids, they must be informed of this without delay.
If the valuation of the bids results in an unreasonably low price, the bidder must be given an opportunity to comment before a possible exclusion of his bid.
The decisions taken during the examination and evaluation of the offers are to be documented in a comprehensible manner.
Divergent regulations
In Germany, the offers to be kept secret may only be made available to those directly responsible for processing them.
The review of the offers as well as the calculation of the bids may only be carried out by the awarding authority.
It has only to employ staff who are not involved in the award decision or the implementation of the measure.
The performance of further examination and evaluation tasks is not regulated.
If freelancers are charged with checking and valuing, they must treat the offers in confidence.
They may only make proposals for the decisions to be made by the awarding bodies.
In the Czech Republic, procurement committees are to be set up to examine and evaluate the bids.
The committees draw up evaluation reports with proposals for awarding contracts.
Ultimately, as in Germany, only the contracting authorities have to decide on the contracts awarded.
If evidence or declarations required for the submission of bids in Germany are not submitted in full, the awarding authority has to give the bidders the opportunity to submit the missing documents within six days.
Only if the documents are still not available after the expiration of the deadline is the offer excluded from the valuation.
In the Czech Republic, it is at the discretion of the awarding authority whether to give bidders the opportunity to complete missing evidence or declarations.
If a bidder fails to do this, he must be excluded.
In Germany, apart from the total price, the unit prices (prices for partial services) of the offers must also be investigated.
If, due to the price structure of the offer, there are indications that the prices for partial services are too low or too high, the bidder must be asked to remove these ambiguities.
If he fails to do so and if the awarding authority can prove that the prices are calculated in a mixed manner, this offer must be excluded.
The aim is to prevent bidders from speculating on significant changes in the volume of partial services when calculating their bid, which can result in significant increases in the cost of the construction projects.
In the Czech Republic, the total price is assessed, but not the adequacy of the prices for partial services.
A mix calculation cannot justify the exclusion of an offer.
In Germany, a surcharge may not be imposed on offers with unreasonably high or low prices.
If one or more bids fall short of the true price determination of the client or the bid sums of the remaining bidders by 10% or more, the bidders must prove the correct calculation of their bids.
If this is not possible for them, the awarding authority can exclude the relevant offers.
In the Czech Republic, the tender can be cancelled after checking the economic efficiency, if only offers with unjustifiable at low prices are available.
In contrast to German public procurement law, the surcharge for offers with prices substantially higher than those of the client cannot be refused for this reason.
If there are suspicions of anti-competitive behaviour in Germany, the awarding authority must immediately report to its technical supervision at the leading level.
It has to decide what measures to take and whether to inform the antitrust authority or the public prosecutor.
For example, the professional supervision at the leading level must also agree to construction work of more than 50,000 euros if the contract is to be awarded by hand, if the bid is not to be awarded at the lowest price or if the tender is to be cancelled.
There are no regulations in the Czech Republic.
