For the construction services, it was usually not clear whether the offers for freelancers were only available to those directly responsible for the work.
Inspection and computational verification of offers
Some awarding bodies passed on the open offers to freelancers for further examination, without having previously carried out the prescribed review of the offers and the computational examination themselves and having documented their results.
In the case of manipulative intentions, third parties could have made changes to the offers without the contracting bodies being able to understand this.
In the documents checked, some conspicuous or missing price or product information were not or only inadequately marked.
Performance audits
For a sample in a building administration, the most favourable offers in three quarters of the tested tendering procedures deviated more than 10% from the estimate costs previously determined.
Each twentieth award procedure was cancelled due to inappropriate bid prices.
Not all of the bidders were able to understand or sufficiently document their bid tests and discussions with bidders.
In many cases, there is a lack of more detailed information, such as on the unit prices of the most important positions.
Frequently, the deviations were only justified in general terms, for example by indications of changed market prices or increased material costs.
The building authorities explained that the detection and detection of mixed calculations is difficult.
In the case of an invitation to tender from an institution under public law, the offer price of the most advantageous offer was 66% below the previously determined estimate value of these services.
Closer calculations or investigations into the causes of this deviation have not been documented.
In a briefing, the awarding authority found no evidence of price dumping by the then contracted company.
This left it unclear whether the estimated value was excessive or whether the offer price was too low.
Later, the client assessed the contracted company as a "low-cost company" that could not maintain quality or deadlines.
In another call for tender, a building services authority awarded the bid, the price of which was 35% higher than the value of the cost assessment.
It did not cancel the call for tender, citing the non-factual reason that an adequate calculation could be concluded for this company.
Suspected irregularities
There were two cases of irregularities in the audited building administration, both of which were reported to the leading authority.
In one of the cases, the calculation of two bidders was identical in a call for tenders, so that the awarding authority excluded both bids from the procedure.
In the application of the other regulations, the tests did not reveal any substantial complaints.
NK
Aptitude test
For many of the approved construction projects, including university construction, road construction and the extension of the rail network, the awarding bodies did not exclude bidders from the procedure, even though they did not meet the requirements specified in the tender documents or could not prove their suitability to the extent required. On the other hand, a tendering body could neither prove nor explain why it had excluded a bidder who had complied with the requirements.
Rating
When awarding construction services for a water treatment plant, the awarding authority omitted the given evaluation criteria when considering and valuing the bids.
In a construction project for the extension of the railway network, the awarding authority determined the weighting of the evaluation criteria only at the beginning of the evaluation.
In the case of road maintenance measures, the given criterion of "shortening the construction phase" was incorrectly evaluated in a procedure.
As a result, the bidders in second and third place did not take sufficient account of the shortfall offered.
Documentation of the selection
In three tendering procedures for housing development, the tendering body did not document the criteria it applied and the basis on which it had selected the successful bidder.
During the construction of a motorway, the contracting authority chose the companies for smaller contracts up to 20,000 Euros on the basis of telephone surveys of prices and delivery conditions alone.
Examinations of this selection were not possible because the surveys were not documented.
Summary findings
The regulations for examining and evaluating the offers in both countries are in line with the requirements of the EU.
However, the details of the procedure and the selection of the people involved differ from one another.
In Germany, the procedure is more closely regulated than in the Czech Republic due to detailed requirements, in particular regarding the implementation of the multi-eye principle and the protection of the offers.
The same applies to the requirements on the basis of which the adequacy of the offered prices must be examined.
In both countries, it had to be established in some of the tendering procedures examined that substantial steps in the examination and evaluation of the bids had not been or had been inadequately documented.
However, without accountability and transparency of the audit and evaluation decisions, possible manipulative interventions are favoured.
A particularly serious defect was the handing over of all offers to third parties, without the public contracting authority having sufficiently looked through and documented the offers beforehand, thus protecting them against possible manipulation in the further proceedings.
If public authorities have tasks carried out during the examination and evaluation of the offers by third parties, sufficient precautions and an increased control effort are required to respond to the increased risk of manipulation.
When examining the appropriateness of the prices, the audited services in Germany did not always make full use of the specified instruments and did not examine the price structure of the offers sufficiently.
In the Czech Republic there have been complaints, particularly regarding the suitability test and the application of the assessment criteria.
Closure of the award procedure
After examining the value of the bids, the award procedure will be completed by the award of the bid or by the suspension of the procedure.
Requirements of EU law and the prevention of corruption
In the case of EU-wide tendering procedures, all bidders must be informed in advance of the planned award decision.
The companies have the possibility to check the intended allocation of information by electronic means or by fax within 10 days or by other means of communication within 15 days and, if necessary, to open a review procedure.
A contract may not be concluded before the expiration of this information period.
