If a bidder submits a request for review within the information period, it is only possible to conclude the contract after the final decision in the review procedure.
Companies can also have the award decision reviewed by an independent court as part of this review process.
The review procedure is intended to ensure legal protection for companies and to encourage the contracting authority to observe public procurement law throughout the entire tendering procedure.
To do this, he must sufficiently document the procedure.
Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
Both countries have implemented the EU rules on information and verification procedures.
In both countries, the awarding authority has to decide on the award of the award.
However, it must not arbitrarily deviate from the result of a proper review and evaluation of the offers.
The client shall place the order within the announced surcharge period,
Also because the bidders are no longer bound to their bids after the deadline.
In the case of open and non-open procedures or public and restricted tenders, the client may not in principle deviate from the content of the offer at the conclusion of the contract.
The underperforming bidders must be informed in a timely manner about the award decision and the reasons for not taking their offers into account.
Tendering procedures may only be cancelled under certain conditions, for example if the bid prices are inflated or the bids do not meet the requirements of the tender.
Divergent regulations
In the Czech Republic, the 10-day or 15-day information and waiting period prior to the award of the contract also applies to construction services not to be awarded throughout Europe.
In Germany, these requirements apply only to the area of EU-wide awards.
In the other proceedings in Germany, bidders can only be informed of the award decision after the award has been awarded.
In the Czech Republic, a tendering procedure has to be cancelled if only one bid has been received or only one bid has been accepted.
In Germany, the award is only to be made in the case of a single, valuable bid, provided that it meets the conditions of the tender and is economical.
