For some contracts, for example in the construction of road maintenance, the construction of a motorway and a bypass, the contracting bodies concluded the contracts after the legal deadline.
When awarding construction work for the refurbishment of the former military site, the awarding authority only forwarded the notice of the award to all bidders after the legal deadline.
Summary findings
Both countries have implemented the requirements of the EU at the end of the tendering procedure.
The legal protection of the underperforming candidates or bidders increases the scope of the prevention of corruption.
The scope of legal protection in Czech public procurement law is also extended to contracts below EU thresholds.
In both countries, time limits for placing orders have been exceeded.
This can lead to economic disadvantages and increase the risk of manipulation.
The building services should in future avoid the identified shortcomings in the completion of their tendering procedures.
Documentation, reporting and reporting requirements
The award procedures are to be documented during their individual stages with regard to the relevant findings as well as the justifications of the individual decisions.
For EU-wide procedures, the orders are to be announced.
The order data is also recorded in an EU statistic.
Requirements of EU law as well as the prevention of corruption The documentation of the procurement procedures implements a fundamental requirement of the EU-wide transparency requirement.
Carefully and promptly produced documentation allows for the traceability of the award decisions.
In particular, it also serves the effective legal protection of bidders for contracts above EU thresholds.
Proper documentation is also an essential part of preventing corruption, as the compulsion to justify award decisions in detail significantly limits the scope for manipulation.
The announcement of a contract in an EU-wide tender procedure has to be submitted to the Office for Official Publications of the EU within 48 days.
The Office publishes the notices in the Official Journal of the EU and thus implements the transparency requirement.
The contracting bodies must also collect the essential data of their procurement procedures and report it to the competent national ministries of the European Commission.
On this basis, the European Commission produces an annual EU statistic, which enables it to gain an overview of the development of the internal market in construction services.
Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law
The same or similar rules
Both countries have fully transposed the EU legal requirements for documentation and reporting requirements into national law.
The rules on documentation and reporting for EU statistics are largely the same in both countries.
Divergent regulations
In the Czech Republic, the obligation to publish awarded contracts is not limited to EU-wide contracts, but also extends to the other tendering procedures.
The notice period is reduced to 15 days.
In Germany, in addition to EU-wide awards, there is a publication obligation only for limited tenders and for freehold contracts with a value limit of 25,000 euros or 15,000 euros without VAT (so-called ex post transparency).
Under these limits and in the case of public tenders, only the companies taking part in the competition procedure will receive information about the contracts awarded.
