Summary evaluation and recommendations
The parallel tests of the NK and the BRH have focused on two main areas, which in the Czech Republic and in Germany are essential for the award of construction services by public authorities: The application of EU procurement regulations and the prevention of corruption.
The requirements of EU law enable cross-border competition to create a single European market.
Anti-corruption measures are not only designed to prevent or at least reduce corruption, but also to avert economic damage and a possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.
The audit findings of the two courts of auditors on the application of the public procurement regulations in both countries, as well as the comparison of these regulations, provide conclusions on similarities and differences that can be helpful for both countries in the further development of their public procurement law and its application.
Application of EU public procurement rules
The EU requirements for the award of construction services have been transposed into national law by both countries.
Thus, in the Czech Republic and Germany, there is an important common basis for the award of construction services and the consideration of the essential bids of the competition, the equal treatment of the companies involved and the transparency of the tendering procedures.
The building services of both countries have in some cases very extensively supported these bids by further administrative regulations.
To a large extent, the Czech Republic has also applied the requirements of the construction contracts to its nationally regulated tendering procedures below the EU threshold.
However, investigations by the Court of Auditors have shown that the building services have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.
The building administration in Germany should further improve the quality of its tendering procedures in order to be able to remove the complaints identified when implementing the EU requirements.
The tests carried out in the Czech Republic have, above all, revealed dangers that affect the efficiency of the contracts.
For example, incomplete descriptions of performance required additional services, which were often awarded in violation of the law. In addition, the cost calculations were mostly inadequately prepared, and excessive qualification requirements reduced the number of possible bidders and, in particular, restricted competition in the construction of roads.
Prevention of corruption
The investigations did not aim to uncover cases of corruption,
Also because the courts of auditors do not have appropriate instruments for this.
However, the courts can check to what extent the administrations of both countries have taken precautions against corruption and manipulation in the award of construction services and how these requirements are applied.
Both countries have set different priorities in the prevention of corruption.
The German regulations foresee, above all, a largely unrestricted competition and transparency and controls as central elements of the prevention of corruption.
The main aim of the Czech regulations is to increase the transparency of procedures.
BRH
In Germany, general principles of prevention of corruption apply, which must be applied by the entire federal administration.
These principles are also implemented in the requirements for the award of construction services and geared towards their specific requirements.
According to the regulations, it is sometimes very clear how the bids for the prevention of corruption are to be taken into account in the course of the tendering procedures and in the selection of the persons involved.
In the opinion of the BRF, in particular, the primacy of the principle of open procedure or public tender is a suitable instrument for substantially reducing the risk of corruption in the award of construction services, while restrictions on competition increase the risk of manipulative interventions.
Risk analysis and sufficient controls (especially the multi-eyes principle), the requirements for transparency and documentation of the award procedures, as well as various organisational measures, are also effective precautions to prevent corruption and manipulation.
The BRH therefore sees no need for change in principle to the corresponding requirements of the administration when awarding construction services.
The rules for preventing corruption are largely taken into account in practice.
The shortcomings identified in some areas have shown shortcomings in the implementation of some requirements.
The building services should continue to train their employees on the requirements for the prevention of corruption and make them even more sensitive to this problem.
A significant part of the complaints related to tasks the building services had delegated to freelancers.
However, without checks and adequate safeguards, the risk of abuse increases when delegating tasks.
Manipulative and corrupt tasks should therefore only be assigned to third parties if the administration can ensure a sufficient level of protection against inadmissible interventions.
NK
At the level of government, the Czech Republic has adopted a strategy against corruption, in which the most important element is the area of public procurement.
The award law and the related implementing provisions have been substantially amended.
The tests of the NK took place during the implementation of this strategy.
The strategy adopted and the new legal provisions should be effective improvement measures, since the awarding bodies must justify the cost-effectiveness of the orders, the calculation of the expected prices, the adequacy of the qualification requirements, the essential evaluation criteria and the type of assessments, and properly document and publish all these aspects.
Recommendations
The NK and the BRH are generally positive about the implementation of the EU guidelines.
The broad acceptance in practice has confirmed that the EU requirements of competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for the award of construction services within the European Union.
The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects to enable and promote cross-border competition.
In view of the enormous material and ideal damage caused by manipulation and corruption in the award of construction services, both courts of auditors see the building services in their countries as being called upon to continue and, if necessary, improve their measures against corruption and manipulation.
In particular, the organisation and procedures of tendering procedures should be continuously examined for weaknesses and risks, in order to identify the need for action and to be able to take appropriate countermeasures.
The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the share of open procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased, as open procedures offer a wider scope for competition and can significantly reduce the risk of corruption.
In addition, a greater division of construction services into lots can have a favourable effect on supply prices, provided that greater competition is achieved with a higher number of bidders.
Ensuring the correct execution of the tendering procedures is an essential basis for efficient contracting of public contracts.
In Germany, the tendering procedures are carried out by the building services specialized in this field, whereas in the Czech Republic, these tasks are carried out - with the exception of the transport projects - by the departments themselves or by the contractors commissioned by them.
After the completion of their joint project, the two countries' courts of auditors will continue to develop the knowledge that is important to them and, if necessary, refer it to the parliament and the government of their country.
In addition, both courts are convinced that the principles of public procurement law set out in this report and its implementation are also of interest at the international level of the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI), because the principles and knowledge set out are of general importance in order to combat corruption effectively and to ensure the economic allocation of construction services in a well-functioning and fair competition.
